m":"Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Annesley, Nottinghamshire,England":"Annesley, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Annesley, Nottinghamshire, England":"Annesley, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1140–28 March 1218":"about 1140–28 March 1218","1140–1218":"1140–1218","1144–Female":"1144–Deceased","1180–1275":"1180–1275","1165–1219":"1165–1219","1182–Male":"1182–Deceased","1184–Male":"1184–Deceased","1106–1207":"1106–1207","1118–Female":"1118–Deceased","about 1140":"about 1140","1165":"1165","1275":"1275","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","28 March 1218":"28 March 1218","1118":"1118","25 November 1207":"25 November 1207","1139":"1139","1106":"1106","1144":"1144","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","1218":"1218","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Annesley, Nottinghamshire,England":"Annesley, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Annesley, Nottinghamshire, England":"Annesley, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Annesley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Ansley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ansley","meanings":["English:","habitational name from such places as Ansley in Warwickshire or Annesley in Nottinghamshire. The former is named with Old English <i>ānsetl</i> ‘hermitage’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’; the latter with an Old English personal name <i>An</i> (‘the solitary one’) + <i>lēah</i>. In North America, the surname may in some cases also be an altered form of Scottish   Ainslie  . Compare   Ainsley  .","variant of   Anslow  ."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph II Annesley was born about 1140, in Annesley, Nottinghamshire, Engla